answer.p:
First of all, the plane in \R^3 is just the set \Span{\vec{3 -2 1}, \vec{-5 6 1}} so the question is asking whether or not u lies in that set. As in previous exercises, this leads to a linear system whose augmented matrix is reduced to echelon form as
\mat{3 -5 0;-2 6 4;1 1 4} \to \mat{3 -5 0;0 \dfrac{8}{3} 4; 0 \dfrac{8}{3} 4} \to \mat{3 -5 0;0 \dfrac{8}{3} 4;0 0 0}
The system is consistent (since the last column is not a pivot column), so u does lie in the given plane.
